    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Kingston</placeName>
                <date>Decr 8th 1857</date>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I regret I should have so far neg-<lb/>lected my duty to you when I
                transmitted<lb/> to your care a communication in which I<lb/> was particularly
                interested, without directly<lb/> addressing you soliciting your kind
                interference<lb/> &amp; influence, to aid me in the accomplishment<lb/> of my
                purpose, this would even of itself<lb/> bear the impression, that I was
                influenced<lb/> by personal motives; but regardless of this,<lb/> permit me to
                assure you, that there was<lb/> something due on other grounds, viz, my<lb/>
                personal respect for your position as a teacher<lb/> in
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName>, and had it not been that I was<lb/> reminded of
                the fact of my negligence I<lb/> should still have remained the defaulter,<lb/>
                although quite unintentional; but, repentance<lb/> never comes too late, and will
                doubtless<lb/> make reparation for my wrong.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have seen your communica-<lb/>tions to <persName>Mr.
                    Nathan</persName>, by which I am con-<lb/>vinced you have interested yourself in
                my<lb/> behalf, for which I have to thank you,<lb/> I regret to learn that there has
                been a division<lb/> in the congregations I should have preferred<lb/> to have heard
                the “two sticks were united”</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>however as congregations are now con-<lb/>stituted I regret to say too much
                dif-<lb/>ference of feeling exists, &amp; too much dis-<lb/>satisfaction prevails,
                Alas! For the poor<lb/> Hazanim, our lot is not always cast<lb/> in pleasant places,
                although we must<lb/> not murmur, I should like to have<lb/> been made aware of the
                mode of living<lb/> domestic expenses &amp;c, so as to form an<lb/> estimate of
                situation <hi rend="underline">&amp; place</hi>; but for<lb/> that I of course have
                to thank myself<lb/> for not seeking your advice in time.<lb/> I may yet not be too
                late, could you<lb/> respond to this promptly, I am happy<lb/> to hear my old friend
                    <persName>Revd S. Jacobs</persName> is<lb/> officiating in your city, and I
                trust<lb/> he may continue long in his occu-<lb/>pation to render the congregation
                the<lb/> benefit of his valuable services.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr. Nathan</persName> in his commu-<lb/>nication to you in
                my behalf, more<lb/> or less represented to you my position<lb/> in the present
                sphere of my labors,<lb/> and gave you a faithful account<lb/> of the nature of the
                difficulties under<lb/> which I am now laboring, and I<lb/> feel within myself that
                nothing but<lb/> a fair field for the <sic>developement</sic> of<lb/> my
                energies—which I am impressed</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>with the conviction would be open for<lb/> me in a strange country—can arouse<lb/> me
                from my now dormant state,<lb/> to render myself useful to any<lb/> congregation,
                however praiseworthy is<lb/> modesty, it is too frequently detrimental<lb/> to our
                interests, yet, we cannot get<lb/> rid of the fact; but that the feeling<lb/> is
                encouraged. I however would pursue<lb/> a different course were I to leave this<lb/>
                for any other place.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Permit me in conclusion<lb/> to thank you for your kind wishes<lb/>
                to further my purpose, and believe<lb/> me to be</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Thine ever very truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <persName role="author">A H DeLevante</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>My Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have taken the liberty to enclose a<lb/> letter under your care to
                    <placeName>Richmond</placeName> which I<lb/> would thank you to forward for
                me</p>
            <p>Not known N E</p>
            <p>Try <placeName>371 Walnut St.</placeName></p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
        </body>
